erited and intensifying challenges arising from Venezuela's status as a petrostate, the class and racial divisions that define its society, and the difficulties of defining what Hugo Chávez termed "socialism for the twenty-first century" have resulted in a tumultuous process of social change. Informed by ethnography, contemporary and comparative political thought, and global political economy, Only the People Can Save the People demonstrates how constituent power is shaping collective identity, political conflict, and infrastructural space in contemporary Latin America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aConstituent powerzVenezuela. 0aDemocracyzVenezuela. 0aPolitical participationzVenezuela. 0aSocial changezVenezuela. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 4aPolitics and Law : Democracy. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 4aPolitics and Law : Politics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2018z978311149142440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438469652423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438469652/original  a978-3-11-149142-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles